WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.360
Hey, I hope this isn't too loud for folks in

00:00:04.360 --> 00:00:04.640
the room.

00:00:04.640 --> 00:00:06.840
The speaker here is busted, so we can't hear.

00:00:06.840 --> 00:00:07.900
Okay, so we're 0 for 2.

00:00:07.900 --> 00:00:12.960
Okay, I will try to be loud while speaking into a

00:00:12.960 --> 00:00:13.380
mic.

00:00:13.380 --> 00:00:14.440
This feels very counterintuitive.

00:00:14.440 --> 00:00:16.140
Hi, folks.

00:00:16.140 --> 00:00:18.540
It is nice to see all your wonderful faces.

00:00:18.540 --> 00:00:21.430
I should start off that this is the same presentation that I

00:00:21.490 --> 00:00:22.020
gave yesterday.

00:00:22.020 --> 00:00:24.040
So if anyone was here yesterday, I'm very flattered

00:00:24.040 --> 00:00:24.240
.

00:00:24.240 --> 00:00:27.520
You should probably leave because you will just be here.

00:00:27.520 --> 00:00:28.360
Or, hey, stay.

00:00:28.360 --> 00:00:29.640
I love the sound of my own voice.

00:00:29.640 --> 00:00:31.000
Maybe you'll love to hear more of it, too.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:34.170
This is part of the At Science Conference, and so I

00:00:34.170 --> 00:00:37.300
toss in this little cheeky joke towards At Social Science because

00:00:37.300 --> 00:00:38.600
I am a social scientist.

00:00:38.600 --> 00:00:41.230
I am a PhD student at the University of Pennsylvania where I

00:00:41.290 --> 00:00:45.820
study communications, specifically the political economy of online spaces.

00:00:45.820 --> 00:00:51.310
When we think about some of the benefits from the At Protocol

00:00:51.310 --> 00:00:55.470
, there are kind of two and a half real main benefits

00:00:55.470 --> 00:00:57.680
for social science researchers.

00:00:59.280 --> 00:01:00.600
The first one is data access.

00:01:00.600 --> 00:01:02.910
So there is this kind of long history of, I should

00:01:03.050 --> 00:01:06.470
say long, long within the history of internet research, concern

00:01:06.470 --> 00:01:09.020
over the access to public social media data.

00:01:09.080 --> 00:01:10.920
And over the last five to ten years, a lot of

00:01:10.920 --> 00:01:12.320
that has been constricted.

00:01:12.320 --> 00:01:14.850
Nowadays, if you're interested in understanding the kind of handful

00:01:14.850 --> 00:01:17.860
of dominant platforms, what you end up having to do is

00:01:17.860 --> 00:01:20.310
either, in the case of Meta, use a really

00:01:20.310 --> 00:01:23.100
clunky system that, like, is really limited in terms

00:01:23.100 --> 00:01:25.250
of the data analysis you're able to do and the amount

00:01:25.250 --> 00:01:27.870
of data you're able to sample, you have to ask

00:01:28.190 --> 00:01:31.760
them for permission in order to conduct any analysis.

00:01:31.780 --> 00:01:33.860
So if you want to do critical analysis of TikTok, you

00:01:33.860 --> 00:01:36.800
have to get TikTok's permission, which feels very counterint

00:01:36.800 --> 00:01:37.320
uitive.

00:01:37.320 --> 00:01:39.140
Or they just charge you a bunch of money, like,

00:01:39.140 --> 00:01:40.830
in the case of, uh, what was formerly known as

00:01:40.830 --> 00:01:43.170
Twitter, they charge you an absurd amount of money that most

00:01:43.210 --> 00:01:45.400
researchers cannot afford, uh, if you want to do things

00:01:45.400 --> 00:01:46.100
the right way.

00:01:46.100 --> 00:01:48.680
So the first thing that's really nice about Blue Sky is

00:01:48.680 --> 00:01:51.850
that, okay, let's put a caveat of permission spaces

00:01:51.850 --> 00:01:51.980
.

00:01:51.980 --> 00:01:53.990
But currently, all the data is public, which means as

00:01:53.990 --> 00:01:57.320
a social scientist, your ability to look at user behavior is

00:01:57.320 --> 00:01:58.900
really, uh, helped.

00:01:59.280 --> 00:02:01.120
Also, uh, so for Greenwood was talking about this

00:02:01.120 --> 00:02:03.980
yesterday, but if you want to do experiments with different algorithms

00:02:03.980 --> 00:02:06.600
, you also have an ability in the generation of custom feeds

00:02:06.600 --> 00:02:07.680
to do some of that testing.

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:10.790
What I'm interested in, though, is the ability to

00:02:10.790 --> 00:02:12.580
ask structural questions.

00:02:12.720 --> 00:02:14.580
And so there's a long history of, uh, media

00:02:14.580 --> 00:02:18.220
scholars looking at how does the ownership and concentration of media systems

00:02:18.220 --> 00:02:21.220
affect the quality of journalism, uh, the quality of conversation

00:02:21.220 --> 00:02:22.960
and reporting, um, but then also, like, what

00:02:22.960 --> 00:02:26.140
are the kind of broader implications for democratic theory and democracy?

00:02:26.560 --> 00:02:28.590
And it's, a lot of folks have thought about this

00:02:29.010 --> 00:02:30.220
generally in the context of the internet.

00:02:30.240 --> 00:02:32.220
Uh, that is, I mean, arguably one of the

00:02:32.630 --> 00:02:34.830
reasons that Mike Masnick wrote that piece in the first

00:02:34.830 --> 00:02:35.120
place.

00:02:35.120 --> 00:02:37.400
But up until recently, we haven't had a lot of

00:02:37.580 --> 00:02:39.520
alternative, uh, sources to look at.

00:02:39.520 --> 00:02:41.210
We can go and look at the history of the 90s

00:02:41.210 --> 00:02:43.460
and the early 2000s to get a kind of indication of

00:02:43.460 --> 00:02:43.780
this.

00:02:43.780 --> 00:02:45.610
But for the most part, it's been really hard to

00:02:45.610 --> 00:02:48.400
ask these structural questions of what is a deconcentrated

00:02:48.400 --> 00:02:50.210
media system actually look like?

00:02:50.220 --> 00:02:52.730
And so it was in thinking of this, I was looking

00:02:52.730 --> 00:02:54.780
at a paper, uh, called, with a great name

00:02:54.780 --> 00:02:56.410
, I was talking in the middleware with you, uh

00:02:56.410 --> 00:02:59.300
, where some social scientists looked at the current status of feeds

00:02:59.300 --> 00:03:02.080
, uh, starter packs, moderation lists, and labels,

00:03:02.260 --> 00:03:04.910
and basically made the argument that most of these were run as

00:03:04.910 --> 00:03:05.750
gift economies.

00:03:05.780 --> 00:03:08.570
If anyone was here in the conversation earlier, um, the

00:03:08.730 --> 00:03:11.370
, the, the PhD student from the University of Washington was

00:03:11.370 --> 00:03:14.060
making a very similar point, which is currently feeds are mostly

00:03:14.060 --> 00:03:15.120
volunteer work, right?

00:03:15.120 --> 00:03:17.200
Folks are putting these together because they care about community.

00:03:17.200 --> 00:03:18.680
They're paying the hosting costs.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:20.460
Now, if you've got a larger feed, um,

00:03:20.460 --> 00:03:22.500
I was talking, uh, with Emily earlier who runs,

00:03:22.500 --> 00:03:25.000
um, uh, the astronomy feed, you know, there

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:28.150
are some of these that are more sustainable and sometimes donations can

00:03:28.150 --> 00:03:29.640
be a real, uh, viable pathway.

00:03:29.640 --> 00:03:32.380
But in that kind of long tail of feeds that are created

00:03:32.380 --> 00:03:35.060
, oftentimes it's, you're volunteering or you just happen

00:03:35.060 --> 00:03:36.480
to care about something specific.

00:03:36.480 --> 00:03:39.760
Um, also supply often outstrips demand.

00:03:39.760 --> 00:03:42.340
And it is, these do tend to be rather centralized groups

00:03:42.340 --> 00:03:44.630
where a handful of feeds get used by a lot, large

00:03:44.630 --> 00:03:45.520
majority of folks.

00:03:45.520 --> 00:03:46.480
There's a long tail.

00:03:46.480 --> 00:03:49.270
So naturally this brought me to the question of my presentation today

00:03:49.430 --> 00:03:51.440
, which is how to centralize this blue sky.

00:03:51.440 --> 00:03:53.170
I mean, we talk about it in the context of being

00:03:53.170 --> 00:03:54.860
this really decentralized platform.

00:03:54.860 --> 00:03:58.660
Um, but it's not always clear that that is the

00:03:58.660 --> 00:03:59.380
case.

00:03:59.380 --> 00:04:01.790
Um, I want to say that I got completely nerd snip

00:04:01.840 --> 00:04:02.820
ed in this topic.

00:04:02.820 --> 00:04:04.740
I'm going to be referencing, um, I mentioned his

00:04:04.740 --> 00:04:06.900
name yesterday, but Cuba, uh, has put together,

00:04:06.900 --> 00:04:08.710
who is not, sadly not here, has put together a

00:04:08.710 --> 00:04:12.260
really good dashboard that today I saw both Rudy and Paul Fra

00:04:12.260 --> 00:04:14.210
zier, uh, Paul Frazee, uh, reference

00:04:14.370 --> 00:04:15.240
in their own.

00:04:15.240 --> 00:04:16.300
So please go check that out.

00:04:16.300 --> 00:04:19.560
And then eight days before this conference, uh, Lawrence came

00:04:19.560 --> 00:04:21.900
and, uh, wrote a blog post about exactly this concern

00:04:21.900 --> 00:04:22.040
.

00:04:22.040 --> 00:04:24.970
So I got completely, completely nerd sniped, but,

00:04:24.990 --> 00:04:26.560
um, let's talk about it.

00:04:26.560 --> 00:04:28.350
So there are kind of two ways you can measure decentralization

00:04:28.350 --> 00:04:28.520
.

00:04:28.520 --> 00:04:30.900
The first is you go to the relay and you say,

00:04:30.980 --> 00:04:33.280
Hey, can you give me all your list of users?

00:04:33.280 --> 00:04:35.180
And then you, or you give me the list of all

00:04:35.180 --> 00:04:37.100
the PDS's that you were querying through.

00:04:37.100 --> 00:04:38.520
And you go to those PDS's and you say,

00:04:38.520 --> 00:04:40.120
Hey, can you give me your list of users?

00:04:40.400 --> 00:04:42.300
And you count that all up and you say, Hey,

00:04:42.300 --> 00:04:44.410
this is how many people are in all these different PDS

00:04:44.410 --> 00:04:44.700
's.

00:04:44.700 --> 00:04:46.220
You combine that, you get your number.

00:04:46.220 --> 00:04:49.870
The challenge is that, especially for smaller data servers is not

00:04:49.870 --> 00:04:52.850
the, they aren't often completing every part of the API

00:04:52.850 --> 00:04:53.020
.

00:04:53.020 --> 00:04:55.090
And so you're not going to get that information fully,

00:04:55.090 --> 00:04:56.950
or they will have, there will be a lot of,

00:04:56.950 --> 00:04:59.550
uh, PDS's where that information is just not as

00:04:59.550 --> 00:05:00.100
clear.

00:05:00.100 --> 00:05:02.100
So the other thing you can do, if you just assume

00:05:02.100 --> 00:05:04.160
that most people are using, uh, D ID, uh

00:05:04.160 --> 00:05:05.790
, PLC D IDs, uh, is you can just

00:05:05.790 --> 00:05:08.350
go through the list of exports and you can say, Hey

00:05:08.380 --> 00:05:11.250
, uh, what does this tell me about the current state

00:05:11.250 --> 00:05:11.960
of the network?

00:05:11.960 --> 00:05:15.400
Because then you will see every time a new identity was created

00:05:15.400 --> 00:05:17.960
and, uh, with what PDS it is associated.

00:05:17.960 --> 00:05:19.280
Do that measurement?

00:05:19.280 --> 00:05:20.570
Think about 99.

00:05:20.570 --> 00:05:22.940
7% of the network is owned by blue sky.

00:05:23.040 --> 00:05:24.560
So 99% of 99.

00:05:24.560 --> 00:05:28.770
7% of users have their information stored on blue skies network

00:05:28.770 --> 00:05:29.120
.

00:05:29.120 --> 00:05:30.960
I should say this information is a little bit out of date

00:05:30.960 --> 00:05:31.100
.

00:05:31.100 --> 00:05:33.410
I would guess it's probably closer to like the low 99

00:05:33.550 --> 00:05:36.000
point something's percent, but the point is that's a

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:36.920
large number now.

00:05:36.920 --> 00:05:38.900
I know what everyone in this room is saying is thinking,

00:05:38.900 --> 00:05:41.240
wait, did he really get this talk yesterday?

00:05:41.240 --> 00:05:42.240
Why is he repeating himself?

00:05:42.240 --> 00:05:43.960
But the thing you're also thinking is, well, this

00:05:43.960 --> 00:05:46.590
might be technically on paper true, but maybe this doesn't

00:05:46.590 --> 00:05:47.860
reflect the actual behavior.

00:05:47.860 --> 00:05:50.590
Maybe the folks who are posting more are the ones who are

00:05:50.590 --> 00:05:52.810
, uh, like who are willing to go out of their

00:05:52.810 --> 00:05:54.300
way to self host their data.

00:05:54.300 --> 00:05:56.280
And so if you look at that as well, you grab

00:05:56.280 --> 00:05:58.730
a sample of the fire hose stream and you say, okay

00:05:58.730 --> 00:06:01.620
, let's look at, uh, where folks are liking

00:06:01.620 --> 00:06:03.820
, uh, where folks are liking, who they're following

00:06:03.860 --> 00:06:05.740
, um, and who's posting.

00:06:05.740 --> 00:06:07.100
Maybe this will get you different numbers.

00:06:07.100 --> 00:06:09.100
Unfortunately, that's really not the case.

00:06:09.100 --> 00:06:10.690
Uh, followers, about 99.

00:06:10.690 --> 00:06:13.040
9% of followers are going to folks on blue skies.

00:06:13.180 --> 00:06:15.820
Uh, same with likes and then posts are a little bit

00:06:15.820 --> 00:06:19.130
higher in that only 98.

00:06:19.130 --> 00:06:23.070
9% of posts are coming from folks on blue skies servers

00:06:23.100 --> 00:06:23.360
.

00:06:23.360 --> 00:06:26.580
Um, so this has a few issues behind it.

00:06:26.580 --> 00:06:28.580
Um, and I want to talk about this in the language

00:06:28.580 --> 00:06:30.240
that we so often do in blue sky, which is what

00:06:30.340 --> 00:06:32.080
if 2022 Twitter happened again?

00:06:32.080 --> 00:06:34.870
What if an investor came in or somebody felt the need suddenly

00:06:35.030 --> 00:06:36.960
to make a bunch of money and they want to take over

00:06:36.960 --> 00:06:37.580
this network?

00:06:37.580 --> 00:06:40.370
Um, how credible is our exit as users?

00:06:40.480 --> 00:06:42.580
How sustainable is this network to that threat?

00:06:42.580 --> 00:06:46.230
Um, the first concern, and this is one that Paul

00:06:46.230 --> 00:06:48.940
identified in a blog post back in February, um, is

00:06:48.940 --> 00:06:51.340
that still isn't, there's not a lot of adoption

00:06:51.340 --> 00:06:51.580
.

00:06:51.580 --> 00:06:54.080
That's what the measuring decentralization actually gets you.

00:06:54.080 --> 00:06:57.080
And part of that goes with these overarching questions of funding,

00:06:57.080 --> 00:06:59.560
but also part of that is just a challenge for users,

00:06:59.560 --> 00:07:00.080
right?

00:07:00.080 --> 00:07:02.240
Users are not always clear about the value they get from moving

00:07:02.450 --> 00:07:03.080
their data abroad.

00:07:03.080 --> 00:07:05.870
I think all of us understand the value of hosting your data

00:07:06.030 --> 00:07:08.470
yourself or going to something like Euro Sky or Black Sky or

00:07:08.470 --> 00:07:11.190
North Sky and having somebody else host your data, but that

00:07:11.190 --> 00:07:13.130
's not always clear to users who might not be willing to

00:07:13.130 --> 00:07:13.580
adopt it.

00:07:13.580 --> 00:07:15.460
Um, and if you think, if you don't believe

00:07:15.460 --> 00:07:17.240
me in that, uh, I would encourage you to do

00:07:17.280 --> 00:07:18.840
what I did a week ago, which is I was visiting

00:07:18.840 --> 00:07:21.170
my grandparents, go to a retirement community, try to explain

00:07:21.170 --> 00:07:22.580
the concept of blue sky to them.

00:07:22.580 --> 00:07:24.350
Um, I do not think it will take you long to

00:07:24.350 --> 00:07:26.520
realize why adoption might be challenging.

00:07:26.580 --> 00:07:29.310
The second is that there is just practically a limit to what

00:07:29.310 --> 00:07:30.520
a protocol can get you.

00:07:30.580 --> 00:07:33.330
Protocols always exist within these kind of broader socio-techn

00:07:33.330 --> 00:07:34.080
ical systems.

00:07:34.080 --> 00:07:36.140
And so there's going to be a limit to the extent

00:07:36.140 --> 00:07:38.940
to which a protocol actually indemnifies you against these concerns

00:07:38.940 --> 00:07:39.080
.

00:07:39.080 --> 00:07:42.360
Um, and the third thing, this is to get,

00:07:42.460 --> 00:07:45.060
just be a brief legal nerd for a second.

00:07:45.080 --> 00:07:48.040
Um, blue sky is incorporated in, uh, Delaware and

00:07:48.040 --> 00:07:50.570
under Delaware law blue sky is what's called a public benefit

00:07:50.570 --> 00:07:51.080
corporation.

00:07:51.080 --> 00:07:52.970
Now this means that if you do some, if you can

00:07:52.970 --> 00:07:55.530
have a mission and if you do something that's against that

00:07:55.530 --> 00:07:58.580
mission, your shareholders can sue you for violating your mission.

00:07:58.580 --> 00:07:59.580
That is great.

00:07:59.580 --> 00:08:00.980
In theory, there are two problems with this.

00:08:00.980 --> 00:08:03.420
The first one is that you don't longer, you can

00:08:03.440 --> 00:08:05.380
change your mission at any point.

00:08:05.380 --> 00:08:07.580
If you have over 50% of the shareholder voting,

00:08:07.840 --> 00:08:10.280
including getting rid of your mission entirely.

00:08:10.280 --> 00:08:12.080
And so if 50 point 50.

00:08:12.080 --> 00:08:14.700
1% of blue sky shareholders said, Hey, actually,

00:08:14.700 --> 00:08:17.320
we don't want to be a public benefit corporation anymore.

00:08:17.320 --> 00:08:18.580
That could be done tomorrow.

00:08:18.580 --> 00:08:20.410
And there's nothing any of us could do to stop it

00:08:20.410 --> 00:08:20.640
.

00:08:20.640 --> 00:08:21.890
The second concern, and that didn't use to be a

00:08:21.890 --> 00:08:22.240
change.

00:08:22.240 --> 00:08:23.640
That's a 2019 law change.

00:08:23.640 --> 00:08:26.740
The second concern is that we don't know what percent of

00:08:26.740 --> 00:08:28.740
like, we know the list of owners vaguely.

00:08:28.740 --> 00:08:31.190
We can see the list of investors and they have posted on

00:08:31.200 --> 00:08:33.280
, they have posted before about who owns it, but we

00:08:33.280 --> 00:08:35.530
don't know how that breaks down percentage wise, right?

00:08:35.540 --> 00:08:37.640
We don't know what percent of blue sky Jay owns or

00:08:37.640 --> 00:08:39.040
Mike, very smart people.

00:08:39.040 --> 00:08:40.240
I've met all of them today.

00:08:40.240 --> 00:08:42.050
Very nice people, but we don't know how that actually

00:08:42.050 --> 00:08:42.640
breaks down.

00:08:42.640 --> 00:08:44.410
And so it's unclear if that 50.

00:08:44.410 --> 00:08:47.310
1% number rep would have to, would represent a coalition

00:08:47.440 --> 00:08:49.730
of most of the owners, or if that could be achieved

00:08:49.840 --> 00:08:52.240
by a couple of investors working together.

00:08:52.240 --> 00:08:54.920
Unfortunately, I'm also not trying to put a turn in

00:08:54.930 --> 00:08:56.180
the punch bowl here.

00:08:56.240 --> 00:08:58.040
So I'm going to end with a little bit of optimism

00:08:58.040 --> 00:08:58.240
.

00:08:58.240 --> 00:09:00.020
I've seen a lot of stuff over the last couple of

00:09:00.020 --> 00:09:02.400
days that have really inspired me, that have made me feel

00:09:02.400 --> 00:09:04.940
a lot better about this concern, though not entirely fixed.

00:09:04.940 --> 00:09:06.970
The first is the idea, and I know Daniel's going

00:09:06.970 --> 00:09:10.520
to talk more about this in this talk tomorrow, of independent

00:09:10.520 --> 00:09:11.940
PLC governance.

00:09:11.940 --> 00:09:14.990
And so that does give you some indemnification where if

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:18.490
the PLC directories were wholly owned by another organization in

00:09:18.490 --> 00:09:22.320
this kind of catastrophic platform takeover situation, maybe you could

00:09:22.320 --> 00:09:25.270
get them, you would get those, your identities would be

00:09:25.270 --> 00:09:27.920
indemnified against that concern, right?

00:09:27.920 --> 00:09:30.710
So we have a different organization that controls all these identities.

00:09:30.760 --> 00:09:32.530
In this worst case scenario, we at least have a third

00:09:32.530 --> 00:09:34.300
party who we can go to and say, "Hey,

00:09:34.300 --> 00:09:37.260
blue sky's trying to fuck us all over, let's

00:09:37.260 --> 00:09:40.040
fix that issue." The second concern with that is even if

00:09:40.040 --> 00:09:42.650
you get your identity migrated over, you still have this concern

00:09:42.650 --> 00:09:43.860
about data ownership.

00:09:43.860 --> 00:09:46.500
And that's where projects like Hubble are really valuable if we

00:09:46.520 --> 00:09:49.140
get this public copy of all the data on the platform.

00:09:49.140 --> 00:09:52.350
That way if you move, you have a third party in

00:09:52.370 --> 00:09:56.360
the independent PLC organization that would give you your identity back

00:09:56.360 --> 00:09:59.020
, and then using the data backups somebody could put together a

00:09:59.020 --> 00:10:00.390
tool to recover your data.

00:10:00.440 --> 00:10:03.230
And this gets a little bit more complicated because of permission spaces

00:10:03.390 --> 00:10:05.840
, but if anyone here is technical and wants to think about

00:10:05.840 --> 00:10:09.680
how you could under the new permission space structure, you could

00:10:09.680 --> 00:10:11.810
help people set up their own backups, please talk to me

00:10:11.810 --> 00:10:11.940
.

00:10:11.940 --> 00:10:13.440
I think that's a great idea.

00:10:13.440 --> 00:10:16.520
Third is the rise of community PDSs like Euro Sky

00:10:16.520 --> 00:10:19.820
, Black Sky, North Sky, all those wonderful folks,

00:10:19.820 --> 00:10:19.820
which are really promising.

00:10:19.820 --> 00:10:23.280
The more we can encourage adoption of these third party things,

00:10:23.280 --> 00:10:24.480
the better.

00:10:24.540 --> 00:10:26.620
And last but not least, because I realize I'm getting

00:10:26.620 --> 00:10:28.200
close to time, is the broader community.

00:10:28.200 --> 00:10:30.630
It has been a really inspiring few days talking to everyone here

00:10:30.660 --> 00:10:30.810
.

00:10:30.820 --> 00:10:32.660
I've had a lot of wonderful conversations.

00:10:32.660 --> 00:10:35.010
After I gave this talk yesterday, I was surrounded by the

00:10:35.120 --> 00:10:37.800
mob of three different blue sky engineers who threatened to break my

00:10:37.800 --> 00:10:38.200
knees.

00:10:38.200 --> 00:10:39.200
I'm kidding.

00:10:39.200 --> 00:10:40.200
They did not.

00:10:40.200 --> 00:10:42.430
But everybody is equally as concerned about this, and folks are

00:10:42.650 --> 00:10:43.660
working really hard.

00:10:43.660 --> 00:10:45.820
And I would just say that there is a limit to what

00:10:45.820 --> 00:10:48.140
we can do technically, but what we can do technically is

00:10:48.140 --> 00:10:49.680
still really important, because what we have to do is we

00:10:49.680 --> 00:10:54.400
have to decrease the lift on users to adopt these alternatives,

00:10:54.580 --> 00:10:59.150
but we also have to reduce the burden and increase their incentive

00:10:59.150 --> 00:10:59.800
to do so.

00:10:59.800 --> 00:11:01.920
And I will leave you with a quote from Lawrence who totally

00:11:01.920 --> 00:11:02.590
nerd sniped me.

00:11:02.660 --> 00:11:03.660
Thank you.
